================ TITANIC DATA VISUALIZATION PROGRAM EXPLANATION ================

1. import seaborn as sns
Imports Seaborn library.

Purpose:
- statistical visualization
- attractive graphs
- easier plotting

sns:
Short name for seaborn.

2. import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
Imports Matplotlib plotting library.

Purpose:
Used for creating graphs and charts.



================ LOAD DATASET ================

3. df = sns.load_dataset("titanic")
Loads Titanic dataset from seaborn.

Titanic Dataset:
Contains passenger information such as:
- age
- gender
- class
- fare
- survival status

4. print(df.head())
Displays first 5 rows of dataset.

Purpose:
Quickly inspect data.

5. print(df.info())
Displays dataset information.

info() shows:
- total rows
- columns
- datatypes
- missing values



================ COUNT PLOT : SURVIVAL ================

6. sns.countplot(x="survived", data=df)

Creates count plot for survival.

x="survived":
Uses survived column on x-axis.

Values:
0 -> Did not survive
1 -> Survived

Purpose:
Count number of passengers who survived and did not survive.

7. plt.title("Survival Count")
Adds graph title.

8. plt.show()
Displays graph.



================ COUNT PLOT : GENDER VS SURVIVAL ================

9. sns.countplot(x="sex", hue="survived", data=df)

Creates grouped count plot.

x="sex":
Gender categories on x-axis.

Values:
- male
- female

hue="survived":
Adds survival categories with different colors.

Purpose:
Compare survival counts between males and females.

Observation:
Females survived more than males.



================ COUNT PLOT : CLASS VS SURVIVAL ================

10. sns.countplot(x="pclass", hue="survived", data=df)

Creates count plot based on passenger class.

pclass:
Passenger class.

Values:
1 -> First class
2 -> Second class
3 -> Third class

Purpose:
Compare survival based on passenger class.

Observation:
First-class passengers had higher survival rates.



================ HISTOGRAM ================

11. sns.histplot(df["fare"], bins=30, kde=True)

Creates histogram of fare values.

fare:
Ticket price paid by passengers.

Purpose:
Understand fare distribution.

12. bins=30

Bins:
Intervals/groups in histogram.

Meaning:
Data is divided into 30 bars.

More bins:
Detailed graph.

Fewer bins:
Simpler graph.

13. kde=True

KDE Full Form:
Kernel Density Estimation

Purpose:
Adds smooth density curve over histogram.

Helps visualize:
- distribution shape
- skewness
- data concentration

14. plt.title("Fare Distribution")
Adds graph title.

15. plt.xlabel("Fare")
Adds x-axis label.

16. plt.ylabel("Count")
Adds y-axis label.

17. plt.show()
Displays histogram.



================ IMPORTANT PLOT TYPES ================

1. Count Plot
Used for:
- categorical data
- frequency/count comparison

Example:
- gender counts
- survival counts

2. Histogram
Used for:
- numerical data distribution
- frequency analysis

3. KDE Plot
Used for:
- smooth probability distribution
- understanding data density

4. Seaborn
High-level visualization library.
Provides attractive statistical plots.

5. Matplotlib
Base plotting library.
Provides detailed graph customization.



================ ABOUT KDE (Kernel Density Estimation) ================

KDE creates a smooth curve representing data distribution.

Purpose:
- identify skewness
- identify peaks
- understand data spread

Without KDE:
Only bars shown.

With KDE:
Smooth curve also shown.



